---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Privacy" description="Vexyn's privacy policy: your prompts and images never leave your device. What little the site itself touches is listed here.">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">Privacy</h1>

    <p class="text-lg text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-8">
      Short version: <strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">by default your prompts never leave your device.</strong>
      There is one exception, it only happens if you pick it, and we tell you before you do — details below.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">The two ways images get made</h2>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">On your device (the default).</strong> If your browser
      supports WebGPU — every desktop browser and recent phones — the model runs inside your tab. Your
      prompt is never transmitted anywhere. Generate an image with DevTools → Network open and you will
      see zero requests.
    </p>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-6">
      <strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">On our server (only if you choose it).</strong> Some
      devices, mostly phones, can't run the model locally. Those visitors are offered a choice: generate
      on our server, or download the model and run it slowly on the device CPU. If — and only if — the
      server option is picked, the prompt is sent to a Cloudflare Worker, passed to the image model, and
      the result is returned. The prompt is not written to any database or log, and the image is not
      stored. A per-connection daily counter is kept so the free capacity isn't drained by one user.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">What we don't do</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] mb-6">
      <li>We don't have accounts. There is no signup.</li>
      <li>We don't store prompts or generated images — on either path.</li>
      <li>We don't run analytics that profile you.</li>
      <li>We don't sell or share data — we don't have any to sell.</li>
      <li>We don't send anything to a server unless you explicitly choose the server option.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">What we use</h2>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-3">
      Vexyn is hosted on Cloudflare. Cloudflare logs aggregate traffic stats (request counts, country,
      response codes) for the infrastructure — standard for any website. We use Cloudflare's
      privacy-friendly Web Analytics, which doesn't use cookies or fingerprint visitors.
    </p>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-3">
      The AI model (~880 MB) and the tokenizer are fetched once from our CDN and from Hugging Face, then
      cached by your browser. Those downloads are the only model-related network traffic — and they
      contain no information about you or what you intend to generate.
    </p>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-6">
      The site is ad-funded. If and when display ads run, the ad provider and what it can see will be
      named here explicitly — an ad network can never see your prompts, because prompts exist only inside
      your tab.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">Browser storage</h2>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Your theme preference lives in <code class="text-[color:var(--color-brand-400)]">localStorage</code>.
      The model weights live in the browser's Cache Storage so you don't re-download them. Both stay on
      your device and clearing site data removes them.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3 mt-8">Verify it</h2>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed">
      Don't take our word for it. The code is on GitHub. Open DevTools → Network, generate an image, and
      watch: zero requests fire. Load the model, disconnect from the internet, and it still works.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
